.planning/milestones/v1.1-phases/04-user-management-data-persistence/04-RESEARCH.md:335:**What goes wrong:** Current GET /api/auth/users (authApi.ts line 211) only checks `req.auth` exists — any authenticated user can list all users.
.planning/milestones/v1.1-phases/04-user-management-data-persistence/04-RESEARCH.md:344:**How to avoid:** Gate the persisted-data fetch on `user !== null`. The `user` state from AuthContext is restored from sessionStorage on mount (AuthContext.tsx line 98), so it is truthy immediately for already-authenticated sessions.
.planning/milestones/v1.1-phases/04-user-management-data-persistence/04-RESEARCH.md:360:### Pitfall 5: localStorage removal leaves stale keys in existing sessions
.planning/milestones/v1.1-phases/04-user-management-data-persistence/04-RESEARCH.md:362:**What goes wrong:** Existing browser sessions still have `emd-saved-searches` etc. in localStorage. After the migration, the server is the source of truth but old data persists in localStorage silently.
.planning/milestones/v1.1-phases/04-user-management-data-persistence/04-RESEARCH.md:364:**How to avoid:** In `performLogout()` in AuthContext.tsx, the four `localStorage.removeItem()` calls (lines 125-128) already exist and handle this. Optionally, a one-time cleanup on DataContext mount (before the first server fetch) can also remove them. The decision is clean break per D-12, so no migration is needed — stale localStorage data is just ignored and will be cleared on next logout.
