   155	## Context
   156	
   157	- **Codebase (v1.6):** ~250 source files, React/TypeScript SPA + Express 5 server + `shared/` pure-TS module
   158	- **Server**: Express 5 production server (server/index.ts) + Vite dev plugins for backward compat
   159	- **Auth flow**: Server-side bcrypt + JWT (HS256), 2FA with fixed OTP, rate limiting with exponential backoff
   160	- **Audit**: Server-side SQLite (data/audit.db), auto-logged by middleware, immutable from client, configurable retention; cohort IDs hashed via HMAC-SHA256 (v1.6)
   161	- **User centers**: Server-enforced center filtering on all data endpoints (Phase 5)
   162	- **FHIR data**: 7 centers (Aachen, Chemnitz, Dresden, Greifswald, Leipzig, Mainz, Tübingen) with deterministic synthetic data (Mulberry32 PRNG)
   163	- **Outcomes**: 4 metrics (Visus, CRT, Treatment-Interval, Responder) with server-side pre-aggregation at >1000-patient threshold; metric selector with `?metric=` deep-link
   164	- **Test surface**: 429 tests passing across 47 files (v1.6 close)
   165	- **Requirements docs**: Lastenheft (RE-EM-LH) and Pflichtenheft (EMDREQ-*) define the formal requirements
   166	
   167	### DSF Integration Architecture (Multi-Site)
   168	
   169	The EMD operates within a four-zone architecture at each site:
   170	
   171	1. **Clinical/Source Zone**: Local source systems, ETL, pseudonymization, site's local EyeMatics-compatible FHIR repository
   172	2. **DSF Site Node**: Local DSF FHIR server + BPE (Business Process Engine), configured with site Organization/Endpoint resources and certificates for inter-site participation. DSF uses FHIR R4 + BPMN 2.0 for workflow orchestration.
   173	3. **Local EMD Backend**: Express app reads ONLY from the local repository or local consolidated FHIR view — never from remote hospitals directly
   174	4. **Browser/UI Zone**: React frontend queries only its own local backend
   175	
   176	**Key architectural principle**: DSF populates/coordinates the multi-site data layer; EMD stays a local dashboard over locally available data. The EMD backend's existing data-source abstraction (local files or Blaze) maps directly to reading from the local repository that DSF keeps populated.
   177	
   178	**DSF responsibilities**: Site-to-site trust, process authorization, transport security, workflow traceability, approval gates
   179	**EMD responsibilities**: User-facing auth/authz, local audit trail, visualization, local business logic
   180	
   181	**Target pattern (Phase 1)**: Pattern A — central consolidation. Each site sends pseudonymized FHIR payloads via DSF into a local consolidated repository. EMD reads from that. Pattern B (federated query) is future work for strict data-minimization scenarios.
   182	
   183	**Future DSF adapter service** (not in current v1 scope): Backend-only module mapping EMD requests to DSF Task payloads, tracking process state, importing validated returned data, surfacing workflow status. Three resource layers: DSF control plane (Task, Organization, Endpoint, DocumentReference), research payloads (EyeMatics FHIR Bundles), local app metadata (request status, job history, provenance, audit links).
   184	
   185	## Constraints
   186	
   187	- **Backward compat**: `npm run dev` must work unchanged — Vite dev plugins stay functional
   188	- **No database**: JSON file storage only for v1; design APIs so DB can be swapped in later
   189	- **On-premises**: Each site runs its own instance; no shared cloud infrastructure
   190	- **Minimal deps**: Express + http-proxy-middleware + jsonwebtoken + jwks-rsa + bcrypt + better-sqlite3
   191	- **Node.js**: Server must run on Node.js >= 20 (same as existing prerequisite)
   192	- **Existing roles**: Keep the 6-role system (admin, researcher, epidemiologist, clinician, data_manager, clinic_lead)
   193	
   194	## Key Decisions
   195	
   196	| Decision | Rationale | Outcome |
   197	|----------|-----------|---------|
   198	| JSON files over SQLite for v1 | No native deps, simpler deployment, fits on-premises philosophy | Implemented (Phase 1) |
   199	| Keycloak prepare-only (no full OIDC flow) | Needs real Keycloak instance to test; middleware abstraction is the hard part | ✓ Implemented (Phase 6) |
   200	| All localStorage to server | Audit compliance requires it; partial migration creates inconsistent patterns | ✓ Complete — audit (Phase 2), data persistence (Phase 4) |
   201	| Raw Node http types for shared handlers | Avoids Express dependency in code shared with Vite dev plugins | Implemented (Phase 1) |
   202	| SQLite for audit log (better-sqlite3) | SQL filtering/sorting beats JSONL for query flexibility; configurable retention with auto-purge; immutable from UI | Implemented (Phase 2) |
   203	| Server-side login with bcrypt + JWT | Passwords must never be in client bundle; JWT format identical for local and Keycloak — seamless provider switch | Implemented (Phase 2) |
   204	| User credentials + centers in data/users.json | Single user record holds passwordHash, role, centers — same schema regardless of auth provider | Implemented (Phase 2) |
   205	| DSF as separate orchestration layer | DSF populates/coordinates multi-site data; EMD reads only local repository. Four-zone model: clinical/source, DSF node, EMD backend, browser. Clean separation of concerns. | Architecture decided |
   206	| EMD never talks to remote hospitals | Express backend reads only from local FHIR store (Blaze or files). DSF upstream pushes data into local store. No direct cross-site communication from EMD. | Architecture decided |
   207	| Pattern A (central consolidation) for v1 | Each site sends pseudonymized payloads via DSF to local consolidated repo. EMD reads from that. Pattern B (federated query) deferred to future. | Architecture decided |
   208	| shared/ module extracted from src/ (v1.6) | Pure-TS cohort math shared between server (aggregation) and client (client-path fallback). Dual tsconfig, backward-compat shims, byte-parity parity test. | ✓ Validated — clean split, no regressions |
   209	| Server aggregation at >1000-patient threshold (v1.6) | Configurable via settings.yaml (default 1000). Below threshold: client path. Above: POST /api/outcomes/aggregate. Both paths converge on identical grid points. | ✓ Validated — byte-parity test proves identity |
   210	| Cohort ID hashed in audit events (v1.6) | HMAC-SHA256 truncated to 16 hex chars. Secret in settings.yaml. hashCohortId reused by aggregation audit event. URL stays clean (no querystring PII). | ✓ Validated — closes CRREV-01 / IN-01 |
   211	| Per-metric CSV flatteners in OutcomesDataPreview (v1.6) | Each metric has its own flattenXxxRows() helper in the component file (locked-decision-3 pattern from Phase 8). No shared utility to avoid coupling. | ✓ Validated — consistent with locked decision |
   212	
   213	## Evolution
   214	
   215	This document evolves at phase transitions and milestone boundaries.
   216	
   217	**After each phase transition** (via `/gsd-transition`):
   218	1. Requirements invalidated? → Move to Out of Scope with reason
   219	2. Requirements validated? → Move to Validated with phase reference
   220	3. New requirements emerged? → Add to Active
   221	4. Decisions to log? → Add to Key Decisions
   222	5. "What This Is" still accurate? → Update if drifted
   223	
   224	**After each milestone** (via `/gsd-complete-milestone`):
   225	1. Full review of all sections
   226	2. Core Value check — still the right priority?
   227	3. Audit Out of Scope — reasons still valid?
   228	4. Update Context with current state
   229	
   230	---
   231	*Last updated: 2026-04-21 after Phase 16 complete — Cross-Cohort Comparison shipped. Milestone v1.7 in progress.*

